# Module Organization & External Contracts

Guidelines for organizing modules and defining external dependencies using the Ports and Adapters (Hexagonal Architecture) pattern.

## Module Structure

Modules live in `modules/{module-name}/` and should be self-contained with clear boundaries.

```
modules/{module-name}/
├── docs/                    # Module-specific documentation
├── src/
│   ├── Actions/            # Business logic (implements incoming ports)
│   ├── Contracts/          # Interfaces defining ports
│   │   └── External/       # Outgoing ports (external dependencies)
│   ├── Http/
│   │   ├── Controllers/    # HTTP adapters (incoming adapters)
│   │   └── Resources/      # Response transformers
│   ├── Models/             # Domain models
│   └── Providers/          # Service providers
├── tests/                   # Module tests
├── routes/                  # Module routes
├── config/                  # Module configuration
├── agents.md               # Agent patterns and guidelines
└── README.md               # Module overview
```

## External Contracts (Outgoing Ports)

When a module needs functionality from external systems (main app, other modules, packages):

### Rule 1: Define Interface in Module

**Location**: `modules/{module-name}/src/Contracts/External/`

Define what the module needs as an interface:

```php
<?php

namespace Modules\Chatly\Contracts\External;

interface UserSearchContract
{
    public function search(string $keyword, array $filters, int $limit): array;
    public function findByUrn(string $urn): mixed;
}
```

### Rule 2: Implement Adapter in Main App

**Location**: `app/Services/{ModuleName}/`

Implement the interface in the main application:

```php
<?php

namespace App\Services\Chat;

use Modules\Chatly\Contracts\External\UserSearchContract;

class UserSearchAdapter implements UserSearchContract
{
    public function search(string $keyword, array $filters, int $limit): array
    {
        // Implementation using App\Models\User, etc.
    }
}
```

### Rule 3: Register Binding in Service Provider

**Location**: `app/Providers/{ModuleName}ServiceProvider.php`

```php
public function register(): void
{
    $this->app->bind(
        \Modules\Chatly\Contracts\External\UserSearchContract::class,
        \App\Services\Chat\UserSearchAdapter::class
    );
}
```

### Rule 4: Inject Contract in Module

**Never** import `App\Models\*` directly in modules. Always use contracts:

```php
<?php

namespace Modules\Chatly\Actions;

use Modules\Chatly\Contracts\External\UserSearchContract;

class SearchParticipants
{
    public function __construct(
        protected UserSearchContract $userSearch
    ) {}

    public function search(string $keyword): array
    {
        return $this->userSearch->search($keyword, [], 10);
    }
}
```

## Anti-Patterns to Avoid

### ❌ Direct Model Imports in Modules

```php
// BAD - Module directly depends on main app
namespace Modules\Chatly\Actions;

use App\Models\User; // ❌ Never do this!

class SearchUsers
{
    public function search($keyword)
    {
        return User::search($keyword)->get();
    }
}
```

### ❌ Static Helper Calls Without Contracts

```php
// BAD - Direct dependency on helper function
namespace Modules\Chatly\Resources;

class ParticipantResource
{
    public function toArray($request)
    {
        return [
            'photo' => get_user_avatar_url($this->user), // ❌ No!
        ];
    }
}
```

### ✅ Use Contracts Instead

```php
// GOOD - Use contract
namespace Modules\Chatly\Resources;

use Modules\Chatly\Contracts\External\UserDisplayContract;

class ParticipantResource
{
    protected static UserDisplayContract $userDisplay;

    public function toArray($request)
    {
        return [
            'photo' => static::$userDisplay->getAvatarUrl($this->user), // ✅ Yes!
        ];
    }
}
```

## Benefits of This Pattern

1. **Decoupling**: Modules don't depend on main app structure
2. **Testability**: Easy to mock external dependencies
3. **Portability**: Modules can be extracted to packages
4. **Flexibility**: Can swap implementations without changing modules
5. **Clear Boundaries**: Explicit interfaces define what module needs

## Dependency Direction

```
Main Application
    ↓ (implements)
Adapter Classes
    ↓ (implements)
External Contracts (Interfaces)
    ↑ (depends on)
Module Actions/Controllers
```

The module depends on **abstractions** (interfaces), not concretions (models).

